* Tue May 26 2026 Steven Pritchard <steve@sicura.us> - 4.0.0
- BREAKING: A bare `include libreswan` now only installs the libreswan package.
  All other resources (the `ipsec.conf` file, policy files, the `ipsec`
  service, firewall rules, PKI, NSS DB, haveged) require explicit opt-in via
  class parameters.
- `/etc/ipsec.conf` is no longer written from a template. Individual fields
  are managed in place with `file_line` and only when the corresponding
  parameter is non-`undef`. Removed `templates/etc/ipsec.conf.erb` and the
  five policy templates under `templates/etc/ipsec.d/policies/`.
- Service management is opt-in via the new `service_ensure` and
  `service_enable` parameters (both default to `undef` — unmanaged).
- Policy files in `${ipsecdir}/policies/{block,clear,clear-or-private,
  private,private-or-clear}` are written only when their corresponding
  `*_cidrs` parameter is set, and removed when listed in `purge_policies`.
- Configuration fields can be removed via the new `purge_settings` array.
- `simp_options::*` Hiera lookups are no longer consulted for defaults; sites
  that relied on automatic opt-in to firewall/PKI/FIPS/haveged must now wire
  those parameters explicitly.
- Many parameters that previously had concrete defaults (`protostack`,
  `plutodebug`, `dumpdir`, `virtual_private`, `private_clear_cidrs`,
  `klipsdebug`, `perpeerlog*`, etc.) are now `Optional[...]` and default to
  `undef`, meaning "not managed."
- The NSS password-update helper script is no longer installed on bare
  `include`; it is now installed by `libreswan::nss` and pulled in
  automatically by `libreswan::nss::init_db`. A new `libreswan::nss_scripts`
  Boolean parameter (default `false`) can be set to install them directly.
- Ships a `simp:defaults` compliance_engine profile under
  `SIMP/compliance_profiles/` that restores pre-4.0.0 behavior for SIMP
  sites (config file fields, policy files, service running+enabled,
  firewall, PKI, haveged, NSS scripts). Activate by installing the
  `simp-compliance_engine` gem and setting `compliance_engine::enforcement:
  [simp:defaults]` in Hiera.

